    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1874-07-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1874-07-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="338" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d338">
                <head>No. 336.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Watson</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Newport, R.
                                    I.</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1874-07-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 30, 1874</date>.
                            (Received August 3.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to your letter of the 27th instant,
                        which I received last evening, I have the honor to inform you that I
                        telegraphed to you this morning as follows, “The boundary-line between
                        Labrador is a line drawn due north and south from the Bay or Harbor of Ance
                        Sablon, inclusive, as far as fifty-second degree of north latitude. (See
                        Imperial Statutes 6, George IV, cap. 59.) Labrador is under the jurisdiction
                        of Newfoundland.”</p>
                <p>I informed you at the same time that I should communicate to you the dispatch
                        on the subject which I expect from Lord Dufferin, so soon as I receive
                        it.</p>
                <p>I regret much if you have been put to any inconvenience by the delay in
                        replying to your note to Sir Edward Thornton, of the 19th of June last.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>R. G. WATSON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
